  "prompt": "What is the value of [math]\\sqrt [i\\pi ] {-1}[/math]?",
  "response": "To calculate \\(\\sqrt[i \\pi]{-1}\\), we need to express it properly. The notation \\(\\sqrt[a]{b}\\) generally represents \\(b^{1/a}\\). So, \\(\\sqrt[i \\pi]{-1}\\) can be written as:\n\n\\[\n(-1)^{1/(i \\pi)}\n\\]\n\nWe can use Euler's formula \\(e^{i\\theta} = \\cos(\\theta) + i\\sin(\\theta)\\). Specifically, \\( -1 \\) can be expressed in the exponential form as \\( -1 = e^{i \\pi + 2k\\pi i}\\) for any integer \\(k\\). Let's use the simplest form, \\( -1 = e^{i \\pi}\\).\n\nSo:\n\n\\[\n(-1)^{1/(i \\pi)} = (e^{i \\pi})^{1/(i \\pi)}\n\\]\n\nBy properties of exponents, this simplifies to:\n\n\\[\n(e^{i \\pi})^{1/(i \\pi)} = e^{(i \\pi) \\cdot (1/(i \\pi))} = e^{1} = e\n\\]\n\nHence, the value of \\(\\sqrt[i \\pi]{-1}\\) is \\(e\\).",
